            <h3 style ="padding-top:80px;">Antenatal Care:</h3>
            <p>
                Antenatal care, also known as prenatal care, is a comprehensive healthcare program designed to support expectant mothers and ensure the well-being of both the mother and the developing fetus during pregnancy.
                This critical stage of healthcare focuses on monitoring, education, and interventions to promote a healthy pregnancy and safe delivery. Here's a detailed description of antenatal care:
            </p><br />
            <p>
                1. <strong>Early Pregnancy Assessment: </strong> Antenatal care typically begins in the first trimester when a woman confirms her pregnancy. Early assessments involve a medical history review, physical examination, 
                and initial blood tests to determine baseline health and identify any potential risk factors.<br />
                2. <strong>Regular Check-Ups: </strong> Throughout pregnancy, expectant mothers attend a series of scheduled prenatal appointments with healthcare providers, usually obstetricians, midwives, or family physicians.
                The frequency of these visits may vary but generally increases as the pregnancy progresses. <br />
                3. <strong>Screening Tests: </strong> Antenatal care includes a series of tests to identify and manage any potential risks or complications. 
                These tests may encompass screening for gestational diabetes, preeclampsia, infections, and genetic disorders.<br />
                4. <strong>Monitoring Vital Signs: </strong> During each appointment, healthcare professionals monitor vital signs,
                such as blood pressure, weight gain, and fetal heart rate, to ensure they remain within healthy ranges.
                <br /><br />
                Antenatal care is a fundamental component of ensuring a healthy pregnancy and a safe delivery. It empowers expectant mothers with knowledge, support, and medical interventions to promote the best possible outcome for both mother and child. Regular prenatal care visits are essential for tracking the progress of pregnancy,
                identifying and addressing any complications, and optimizing the overall health and well-being of both the expectant mother and the unborn baby.
            </p>

